      "grammarTip": "<h3>Pr√§positionen mit Dativ</h3><p>Certain prepositions in German are always followed by the <strong>Dativ</strong> case. This means the noun and its article that follow the preposition must be in the dative form.</p><p>The most common dative prepositions are: <strong>aus, bei, mit, nach, seit, von, zu, gegen√ºber, ab</strong>.</p><ul><li><strong>aus:</strong> from / out of</li><li><strong>bei:</strong> at / near / with</li><li><strong>mit:</strong> with / by (transport)</li><li><strong>nach:</strong> after / to (cities, countries without articles)</li><li><strong>seit:</strong> since / for (a period of time)</li><li><strong>von:</strong> from / of</li><li><strong>zu:</strong> to (people, buildings, smaller places)</li><li><strong>gegen√ºber:</strong> opposite</li><li><strong>ab:</strong> from (a point in time, usually future)</li></ul><h4>Article Changes in Dativ</h4><p>Remember how articles change in the Dativ case:</p><table class=\"grammar-table\"><thead><tr><th>Gender</th><th>Nominativ</th><th>Dativ</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Masculine (m)</td><td>der / ein</td><td><strong>dem / einem</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Feminine (f)</td><td>die / eine</td><td><strong>der / einer</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Neuter (n)</td><td>das / ein</td><td><strong>dem / einem</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Plural</td><td>die / keine</td><td><strong>den / keinen +n</strong></td></tr></tbody></table><h4>Contractions (Short Forms)</h4><p>Some prepositions merge with the article 'dem' or 'der'. These are very common and should be used in everyday speech.</p><ul><li><strong>zu + dem ‚Üí zum</strong> (Ich gehe <strong>zum</strong> Arzt.)</li><li><strong>zu + der ‚Üí zur</strong> (Ich fahre <strong>zur</strong> Schule.)</li><li><strong>von + dem ‚Üí vom</strong> (Ich komme <strong>vom</strong> Bahnhof.)</li><li><strong>bei + dem ‚Üí beim</strong> (Ich bin <strong>beim</strong> Lernen.)</li></ul>"
